Beijing's Natural Ecology Continues to Attract More Than 500 Species of Wild Animals to "Settle" in City - CNN.com
2020-07-26 05:03:17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sishuo
Capital's Natural Ecology Continues to Attract Wild Animals to "Settle" Cities
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
This newspaper (reporter Wang Bin) Beijing Youth Daily reporter learned from the Municipal Landscaping Bureau that in recent years, with the continuous improvement of the natural ecological environment in the capital, the species and number of wild animals have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals living in Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including brown horse chickens, black storks and other national-level protected animals, as well as impala, whooper swan, gray crane, mandarin duck and other national-level protected animals.
Whether it is planted in an urban forest in the Second Ring Road or a small wetland embedded between buildings, it not only brings the wild interest of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to "settle" in the city.
In the middle of summer, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of vitality.
A raccoon was playing leisurely by a mountain stream, while two badgers were fighting with each other.
In retrospect, a wild boar could not resist the "prickly scratches" on its body and was rubbing against the bark. Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Administration, said that by the end of 2019,178 species of wild animals, including the golden eagle, the spoon chicken and the impala, were living in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares. Nearly one-third of the wild animal species in the city can be seen here.
"In Matsuyama, wild animals are the real'owners' and our staff can only be regarded as the'bodyguards' of others at best."
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the wildlife situation in the protected area on the ground, more than 30 professional patrol team members patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes every day. There will also be a "big circle" once a month, and they will spend a whole day almost walking through the whole protected area.
"During the inspection, it is necessary not only to check and record the biodiversity, but also to check the installation of artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install infrared cameras in the field and so on."
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in the Songshan National Nature Reserve to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli said that with the increasing biodiversity of the protected areas in recent years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the camera. Ocelots, raccoons and pigs and badgers have become "resident guests," and the "appearance rate" of the impala, a Grade II protected animal of the state, has become higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, director of the wildlife and wetland protection department of Beijing Landscaping Bureau, said that the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals in Beijing has increased from 461 in 1994 to more than 500 now, and the species and number of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
The presence of wild animals in cities is becoming more and more common, which is closely related to the escalation of urban greening in the capital city in recent years.
In particular, a new round of afforestation and afforestation of one million mu, which began in 2018, proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological function of forestland and green space, and highlight the concept of "near nature."
Planning strives to interconnect and interact with the surrounding green areas, making it easier for wild animals to "visit friends and relatives," and planting trees that are the animals' favorite source of honey and food plants.
Black Land "Planted" for Agricultural Modernization - Xinhuanet
Harbin, July 26,2020/PRNewswire/-- Black land "planted" to modernize agriculture.
In midsummer, two spraying planes skimmed the 10,000-acre high-yield demonstration field at the Second Operating Station of the Fifth Management Area of Friendship Farm, forming two white lines. In the green field, the words "the world's first field" planted with black rice seedlings stood out in large letters.
Kong Lingqiang, the station manager, said the aircraft could spray more than 6,000 acres of arable land a day, with an efficiency of about eight times that of an unmanned aerial vehicle and hundreds of times that of a human.
This farm is located in the Friendship County of Heilongjiang Province, the largest grain producing province in China. From the sound of "swish" rice cutting in the past to the sound of "rumble" in the present, traditional Chinese farming and farming have transformed in this black soil belt.
In addition to airplanes, satellites are also used in the modern agricultural production of Friendship Farm.
According to Kong Lingqiang, on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to achieve accurate fertilization, reduce agricultural input and reduce pollution. On the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the standard operation level of agricultural machinery in the field.
In the course of this year's rice production, the farm expanded the operating area of satellite navigation unmanned transplanting technology from 3,000 mu last year to 30,000 mu.
This technology makes the planting of seedlings more uniform, maximizes the use of sunlight and arable land resources, and saves 16 yuan per acre in labor costs.
Farms have experimented with new technologies such as informatization and intelligentization in agricultural production, forming the largest cluster of agricultural machinery in China from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, the total amount of farm machinery is 49,000 units (pieces), and the comprehensive mechanization rate in the field is 99.8%.
The operation of agricultural machinery realizes 100% GPS satellite navigation, 100% precision sowing in dryland and 100% high-powered locomotive operation in dryland.
"Green agriculture, smart agriculture and digital agriculture are the pathfinding directions for agricultural modernization."
Said Liu Hualian, director of Friendship Farm.
The key to agricultural modernization lies in scientific and technological progress.
In recent years, Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation, represented by farms, has played an exemplary and leading role in modernizing large agricultural "aircraft carriers," and initially established a modern agricultural industry system dominated by large-scale planting, standardized production, and industrial management.
On the outskirts of Friendship County, there is an agricultural machinery expo park covering an area of 350,000 square meters.
More than 140 sets (pieces) of agricultural machinery and tools introduced and used by Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation over the years are on display here.
These agricultural machinery and farms have witnessed the development of China's agricultural modernization.
She Xiaojia for Everyone - Anhui Hefei Jiang Kou He Lianwei Mass Transfer Direct Attack - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26,2008Subject: She Xiaojia for Everyone - Anhui Hefei Jiang Kou He Lianwei Mass Transfer Direct Attack
Xinhua News Agency reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu and Liu Xia Cun
At 4 p.m. on July 25, Fu Kunbao, dressed in mud-covered galoshes, went to the back of the house and went back and forth with his wife, Zhou Yan, to pick up their belongings.
"I was still gathering grass in the field when I received a call from the village cadres asking for a transfer."
Fu Kunbao said that he has transferred more than 60 acres of land and planted rice, and is now growing well. "Yesterday, he took medicine, and his tools and everything have not been cleaned up," he said.
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer placed in the corner. "No one wants their home to be flooded, so let's make a small home for everyone."
In order to cope with the continuous high water pressure and possible heavy rainfall in Chaohu Lake, Hefei City, Anhui Province, is preparing to open the Jiangkou River Lianwei, where Fu Kun Baojia is located, on the 26th for flood storage.
Jiang Kou He Lianwei is located in Feixi County, adjacent to Chaohu Causeway.
There are thousands of villagers involved in Yan Dian Township and Sanhe Town in Wei who need to be transferred.
As of 16:00 on the 25th, the water level of Chaohu Lake, the fifth largest freshwater lake in China, remained at a high of 13.2 meters, exceeding the guaranteed water level by 0.7 meters.
Fu Kun Bao's kitchen was clean, with a pot of pumpkin heads on the table, eggs and some halogen in the fridge.
"I didn't expect to move. The water in Jiang Kou River is looking good at the moment."
Zhou Yan said that the family home is a bungalow, and some large objects have not yet figured out where to put them.
"First, pack up your valuables. Large items such as refrigerators and TV sets can be temporarily placed in the homes of neighbors or relatives on high ground."
Wang Li, a village cadre, gave Fu Kun Bao his advice.
Wang Liwen is responsible for the transfer and resettlement of 13 villagers, one household notice, confirming the resettlement plan for each individual.
The nearest settlement to Fu Kun Baojia is Su Primary School in Yan Dian Township, which is about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to the large pieces, Fu Kunbao and his wife also had a headache of more than 1,000 kilograms of grain and some new furniture.
"The food is ready to be dragged to relatives' houses, and there is no way to move the furniture."
As soon as the couple discussed it, they put a stool under the newly bought bed and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6:00 pm, Fu Kunbao began to use a tricycle to transport things to relatives' homes, and Zhou Yan continued to tidy up at home.
At 11 o'clock in the evening, the couple looked at the front and back of the house, pulled on the electric switch, and prepared to go to the settlement.
"I hope the water will recede soon."
Fu Kunbao said.
At 9:30 a.m. on July 26, the reporter saw at the scene of Jiang Kou Helianwei that the local area had made all the preparations before the flood.
