Church fire in Nantes, France: Parish volunteer pleads guilty to arson for being kind and taciturn
According to foreign media reports, on July 18, the famous Cathedral of St. Peter and St. Paul, a gem of religious and historical buildings in Nantes, France, was severely damaged in a fire, and the grand organ was completely destroyed.
On the 26th, local time, prosecutors in Nantes announced that a parish volunteer in charge of the defense of the cathedral had been indicted on charges of "arson and destruction."
He has admitted that he lit the fire in the church.
Local prosecutor Cenas said the 39-year-old parish volunteer from Rwanda admitted to lighting fires in three places in the cathedral during the night.
The man's lawyer said that the arsonist now regretted doing such a thing.
The man entered France a few years ago by way of asylum, and was sheltered in the parish where the fire broke out, and taken in in the church.
Prosecutors pointed out that recently, he tried to renew his visa and was talking to the police department about it.
But the church said it still could not believe that the usually kind, smiling, but not very talkative believer would destroy the church he loved so much.
On July 18, the day the fire broke out, the volunteer had already been questioned by the police because of illogical problems in his narration, but he was later released.
The picture shows firefighters carrying out rescue at the scene.
On the evening of the 25th, the man was arraigned again because the professional engineers of the Paris Central Police Laboratory had obtained new evidence.
This time, the man confessed to the act of arson.
The suspect could face up to 10 years in prison and a fine of 150,000 euros if convicted of intentionally setting fire to the property, according to reports.
The fire caused severe damage to St. Pierre and St. Paul's Cathedral, where the organ was completely destroyed and the stained glass windows behind the organ were also severely damaged, the report said.
Brunet, the chief architect of France's historic buildings, said it was a conservative estimate that the restoration of Nantes Cathedral would take at least three years.
Comprehensive news: Us unilateralism undermines bilateral relations International public opinion supports China's countermeasures against the US - Xinhuanet
Beijing, July 26,2020/PRNewswire/-- On the morning of July 24, the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs informed the US Embassy in China that China has decided to revoke the license for the establishment and operation of the US Consulate General in Chengdu and put forward specific requirements for the Consulate General to cease all operations and activities.
International public opinion believes that the unilateralist measures taken by the United States have caused serious distress to the relations between China and the United States, and it is legitimate and necessary for China to respond to the unreasonable provocation by the United States and take countermeasures.
Andrés Borques, director of the China Studies Center at the Institute of International Studies at the University of Chile, said the unilateralist measures by the United States have undermined the bridge of understanding between the Chinese and American people and caused a crisis in the relations between the two major powers.
China's notice to the United States to close its consulate in Chengdu is a countermeasure to the unilateral measures taken by the United States and is in line with diplomatic practice.
Patricio Giusto, a professor at the Catholic University of Argentina and director of the Center for Arab-Chinese Studies, believes that China's decision is a legitimate and necessary countermeasure to previous US provocations, and is not aimed at ordinary Americans.
By pressuring China to cover up its poor response to the coronavirus pandemic, the United States is trying to divert the attention of Americans.
Bambang Suryono, chairman of the Asian Innovation Research Center, an Indonesian think tank, said that the provocative diplomatic posture of the United States has caused serious distress to the relations between China and the United States, and the bilateral relations face serious challenges.
China's notice to the United States to close its consulate in Chengdu is a normal countermeasure and conforms to diplomatic practice. It not only reflects China's principled position of resolutely safeguarding its own interests, but also reflects China's reasonable and advantageous diplomacy.
Tanzanian commentator Francis Semwinza said China's decision was a legitimate and necessary response to the US provocation.
For China-US relations to return to normal, the US should take the initiative to improve its relations with China and stop interfering in China's internal affairs.
The United States should focus on how to achieve win-win economic and political outcomes with China, and how to benefit the two peoples and the entire international community.
Ali Youssef, executive director of the Sudan-based Federation of Arab-Chinese Friendship Associations, said the countermeasures China was forced to take were a legitimate and necessary response to the unreasonable actions of the US, in line with international law and basic norms governing international relations, as well as diplomatic practices.
Earlier, the US called for the closure of the Chinese Consulate General in Houston, seriously violating international law and basic norms governing international relations.
It is hoped that the US side will rescind the previous decision and create necessary conditions for the relations between the two countries to return to normal.
Singapore's Lianhe Zaobao newspaper said in an editorial that the greater strategic intention of the United States is to contain China and prevent China from rising further.
In the face of the United States' step-by-step pressure, China is reluctant to see the relationship between China and the United States continue to deteriorate, but has to take countermeasures.
