It is understood that the joint operation involved a total of 8 ships and 2 helicopters, divided into multiple action groups to coordinate operations and carry out a full-chain crackdown on smuggling at sea and illegal operations on land. All 35 major criminal suspects were present in the case.
At present the case is under further investigation.
The relevant person in charge of the Guangdong Coast Guard Bureau said that in the future, it will continue to maintain a high-pressure posture, crack down on all kinds of illegal and criminal smuggling activities at sea, and maintain good order in the waters under its jurisdiction.
Hurricane Hannah Makes Landfall in Texas or Causes River Surge and Flash Floods - CBS Los Angeles
July 26 (UPI) -- Hurricane Hannah made landfall in the U.S. state of Texas at 5 p.m. local time, bringing strong winds, heavy rain, swollen rivers and potentially life-threatening flash floods.
The National Hurricane Center said Hurricane Hannah is expected to bring heavy rain across parts of southern and northeastern Texas, which could lead to some swollen streams and life-threatening flash flooding.
The worst affected by Hurricane Hannah is south of Corpus Christi to the mouth of the Rio Grande River, while widespread flash flooding is possible in the Rio Grande Valley, the report said.
"Any hurricane is a huge challenge," Texas Gov. Greg Abbott said on Friday.
Thirty-two counties in the state are under a state of disaster emergency because of the hurricane.
Corpus Christi, a city of more than 320,000 people, has closed its libraries and museums, leaving residents waiting in the wings.
Abbott also said the hurricane cannot be allowed to inflict more casualties on Texas at a time when the state is being hit hard by the coronavirus pandemic.
According to reports, 6 to 12 inches of rain is expected to fall in southern Texas overnight on the 26th, and 3 to 5 inches of rain will fall in northern Texas and coastal Louisiana.
Due to global warming and other factors, "Hannah" formed earlier than previous Atlantic hurricane seasons.
Typically, the first hurricanes in the Atlantic Ocean do not form until mid-August.
Poland to withdraw from European treaty to prevent violence against women
Poland will take steps next week to withdraw from the European Treaty on the Prevention of Violence against Women, the Ministry of Justice said Saturday.
Poland's right-wing government cabinet said the treaty, which requires schools to teach students about gender issues, trampled on the rights of parents.
At a news conference, Poland's justice minister, Gioblo, said his ministry would ask the Ministry of Labor and Family on Monday to begin withdrawing from the treaty.
That treaty is also known as the Istanbul Convention.
"The treaty contains elements of what we consider to be harmful meanings and morphological properties," Gioblo said.
Poland's ruling Law and Justice party and its coalition partners are closely allied with the Roman Catholic Church and advocate a conservative social agenda.
Polish President Andrzej Duda has made hostility to gay rights one of his main issues during his successful re-election campaign this month.
On Friday, tens of thousands of Poles, mostly women, protested in Warsaw and other cities against the withdrawal of the convention.
"The purpose of withdrawing from the treaty is to decriminalize domestic violence," Lempart, one of the organizers of the protest, said at a protest march in Warsaw.
Some protesters carried banners that read "Law and Justice is a hell for women."
The Law and Justice Party has long complained about the Istanbul Convention.
Poland's previous centrist government ratified the pact in 2015.
The Law and Justice government has said the treaty does not respect religion and requires liberal social policies to be taught in schools.
So far, however, the party has not decided to withdraw from the convention.
(According to a Reuters report)
