FAA scrambles to check 2,000 Boeing jets for possible engine stall - Xinhua
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737 NG and 737 Classic airliners registered in the United States. The reason is that the air check valve of these airliners is corroded and may cause the engines to stop in the air.
The FAA said it has so far received four reports of 737 NG and 737 Classic aircraft engines stopping in the air, prompting an urgent inspection request for airliners that have been parked for seven days or more and those that have flown fewer than 11 times since they were put back into service.
The FAA warned that the fifth stage check valve on all two engines of the airliner, if corroded, could become stuck in the open position, causing the airliner to lose power completely and not be able to restart its engines.
The aviation regulator ordered that if the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline operator must replace the critical component before the airliner can be put into service again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the coronavirus outbreak had reduced travel demand, leaving many airliners mothballed or less in use, and "the check valve is more susceptible to corrosion."
At the same time, Boeing said it has advised airline operators to inspect the airliners involved in the directive. If problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in overhauling and replacing the check valves.
The Associated Press reported that major U.S. carriers typically fly multiple flights in a day, but after the outbreak of the coronavirus pandemic, a large number of airliners were grounded. With the recent slow growth in demand for passenger travel, some airliners are back in service.
The FAA did not release the details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its airliners was en route from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15 when one of its engines suddenly stalled and the airliner made a successful emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the plane's engines and had inspected the engines of six airliners as directed by the Federal Aviation Administration.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that their airliners did not have engine stalls associated with the air check valve.
Four American Airlines jets will be inspected and 28 United Airlines jets will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect 20 of its jets, but did not say whether there had been any engine stalls.
The FAA's emergency airworthiness directive is another blow to Boeing, according to multiple media reports.
Indonesia's Lion Air and Ethiopian Airlines each crashed a Boeing 737 MAX in October 2018 and March 2019, killing a combined 346 people.
The series of airliners were subsequently grounded worldwide, with production halted in January and resuming in May.
FAA Administrator Steve Dickson admitted in June that the FAA had "erred" in its oversight of Boeing over the 737 MAX.
