Chief Secretary for Administration of Hong Kong SAR Government: The situation is grim and all efforts are being made to fight the epidemic - CNN.com
Hong KONG, July 26,2020/PRNewswire/-- Chief Secretary for Administration of the Hong Kong SAR Government, Mr Matthew Cheung Kin-chung, said on July 26 that the situation of the COVID-19 pandemic in Hong Kong continues to be grim. If the epidemic situation deteriorates, the SAR Government will resolutely adopt more stringent control measures to further restrict the operation of business premises and reduce the space for people to go out.
But at this stage, the SAR government has no intention to introduce a "stay-at-home order" or a "foot-ban" to restrict people from going out.
On the same day, Zhang Jianzong published an online blog entitled "The Situation Is Grim and Fighting the Epidemic with All Its Power."
He said that this wave of the epidemic is the most severe in six months, and the next two weeks will be critical to try to prevent the virus from spreading further in the community.
Apart from the necessary measures taken by the SAR Government, it is also very important for citizens to be self-disciplined and cooperative.
He urged the public to stay at home as much as possible, reduce social contact and eat out.
Members of the public should cooperate with the mandatory wearing of face masks to protect themselves and others, and pay attention to personal and environmental hygiene and frequent hand washing. They should also suspend non-essential family and friends gatherings or dinners and reduce their visits to the market.
He said that the central government has always been very concerned about the changes in the epidemic situation in Hong Kong and supported the anti-epidemic work of the SAR government. He also responded positively to the latest request of the Chief Executive, and provided assistance in increasing the testing capacity and retrofitting AsiaWorld-Expo into a "square cabin hospital" like this one.
Mr Cheung said that the free virus testing provided by the HKSAR Government for specific high-risk groups, namely elderly care homes, disabled care homes and nursing home staff, restaurant staff, taxi drivers and property management staff, has been fully rolled out, involving up to 400,000 people.
He is very concerned about the cases of infection in residential care homes for the elderly. The SAR Government has arranged a specific temporary quarantine centre for residential care homes for the elderly.
He said that the HKSAR Government is building an isolation and quarantine facility near the Penny's Bay Quarantine Centre on Lantau Island in the New Territories, which is expected to provide an additional 700 isolation units by the end of September.
The Chief Executive also announced on the 19th that the HKSAR Government will build an additional 2,000 isolation rooms at the Penny's Bay Quarantine Centre and aim to complete them by the end of this year.
Together with the 800 isolation and quarantine centres already in use, Penny's Bay Quarantine Centre is expected to provide a total of 3,500 isolation rooms by the end of the year.
Hong Kong currently has four quarantine centres in operation, providing a total of about 2,600 isolation rooms.
In addition, the Lei Yue Mun Park Resort on Hong Kong Island was re-opened by the SAR Government on the 24th as a community isolation facility for the treatment of patients under the age of 50 with independent self-care capacity.
