U.S. Congressman John Lewis, a civil rights fighter, was remembered as a "fighter for the weakest" at a memorial service for him on Saturday, July 25.
Lewis' public memorial service has been held in Alabama since Saturday.
There were two memorial services on the first day.
At a public memorial service at Troy University in Alabama on Saturday, Lewis' five siblings and a nephew spoke of him as a loving, fearless man who put his family first.
"He devoted his life to helping others," Henry "Grant" Lewis, Lewis's youngest brother, said at the meeting.
Samuel Lewis said his mother had warned John "not to get into trouble, not to get into trouble."
He added that John did not heed his mother's warning, saying, "We all know that John is always in trouble, always in trouble, but that is because he insists on doing the right thing, and that is a good trouble."
Lewis' siblings reminded those at the memorial service that John's most famous argument was to cause "good trouble," that is, to not shy away from stirring up trouble for the sake of justice.
John had applied to Troy University in Troy, Alabama, where he was born, but Troy University, an all-white school at the time, rejected his application.
John Lewis, who preached the gospel to chickens on his family's farm as a child, eventually earned a degree in religion and philosophy from Fisk University.
Years later, the University of Troy awarded Lewis an honorary doctorate.
Doug Jones, a congressman from Alabama, said the current protesters "are protesting peacefully and nonviolently," as Lewis did during the civil rights movement.
