Koksiri Tibetan Antelope Enters Return Season - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency Xining on July 25 (reporter Wang Jinjin) learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of the Kexili Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration that monitoring showed that the Tibetan antelope, which had been migrating to the Zhuo Nai Lake area in the hinterland of Kexili, was ending their calving and began to return to their original habitat with their calves.
Surveillance footage near the Wudaoliang Protection Station shows that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelope led three Tibetan antelope calves through the 3002-kilometer Qinghai-Tibet Highway and the Wudaoliangbei Bridge of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway, and the Tibetan antelope has already begun to move back.
Experts have analyzed that in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope calves among the relocated flocks has accounted for a quarter to a fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope herds.
Lian Xinming, Associate Researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "In the early stage of relocation, the Tibetan antelope faced a higher risk of predation. Therefore, the number of young in the flock will be relatively small, and there may even be no young in the flock."
According to statistics from the Kexili Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelope relocating has been increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelope relocating was 4,860, an increase of 338 compared to 2018.
Lian Xinming said: "This year's relocation of Tibetan antelope is expected to end in early September, and the number of relocated Tibetan antelope is expected to continue to increase."
The Tibetan antelope is a protected animal at the national level.
Every year at the end of May, Tibetan antelope from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet, Alshan in Xinjiang and other places go to Zhuo Nai Lake in the hinterland of Kexili to lamb.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert on Tibetan antelope conservation in China and a researcher at the Shaanxi Provincial Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said: "The relocation of Tibetan antelope is the process of female Tibetan antelope returning to their habitats after calving. At first, the relocation groups leaving the calving grounds are quite large, but then the Tibetan antelope will return to their respective habitats according to different geographical populations and along different paths."
In order to ensure the safe relocation of Tibetan antelope herds, the reporter learned that recently the Kexili Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has arranged staff to carry out video monitoring and district patrols in the main relocation areas.
If a Tibetan antelope herd is found trying to cross the highway, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time, allowing the sheep to pass through the wildlife passage safely, so as to ensure as little human disturbance as possible on the way back to the mountain.
So, how to relieve the heat in the daily life?
Experts suggest going out in summer to avoid the hot period, preferably not to walk or work in the hot sun around noon, because the sun is most intense during this period, and the possibility of heatstroke is higher.
If you must go out at this time, be sure to do a good job of protection, such as wearing a parasol, a visor, sunglasses, the best conditions to apply sunscreen, to protect against sunburn.
As far as possible, choose light-colored, breathable cotton, hemp and silk textures, and wear less chemical fiber clothing, so as not to dissipate heat in time when sweating a lot, causing heatstroke.
When the weather is hot and sultry, you should prepare enough water to drink in time. Don't wait for thirst before drinking water, because once you feel thirsty, your body is already short of water. Each time you drink water, limit it to 150ml to 200ml. Drink warm water and don't drink ice water.
According to the temperature, the average person drinks 1.5 liters to 2 liters of water per day, and the high temperature workers drink 3 liters to 5 liters of water per day.
When sweating more, some salt water can be properly replenished to make up for the loss of salt in the body due to sweating.
In addition, the human body is prone to lack of potassium in summer, which makes people feel tired and tired. Potassium-containing tea is an excellent summer drink.
In summer, eat fruits and vegetables with high water content, such as lettuce, cucumbers, tomatoes, etc.; fresh fruits, such as peaches, apricots, watermelons, melons, etc. with water content of 80% to 90%, can be used to replenish water; dairy products can not only replenish water, but also meet the nutritional needs of the body.
In addition, people who work in high-temperature environments should appropriately supplement drinks containing potassium, magnesium and other elements.
Summer days and nights are short, the temperature is high, the body's metabolism is strong, consumption is also large, easy to feel fatigued.
Adequate sleep can relax the brain and the body's systems, which is not only conducive to work and study, but also a measure to prevent heat stroke.
Experts say the best time to go to bed is between 22:00 and 23:00, and the best time to wake up is between 5:30 and 6:30.
When sleeping, be careful not to lie under the air conditioner outlet and electric fan, so as not to suffer from air conditioner disease and heat colds.
Experts suggest that people who are engaged in outdoor activities or high-temperature operations can carry ten drops of water, Rendan, Patchouli Zhengqi water or Patchouli Zhengqi pills and other anti-heat medicines, or place them in the nearest workplace and use them at any time to prevent the occurrence of heatstroke.
