Hami, Xinjiang, July 26,2016/PRNewswire/-- "Sunflower Fields" in Xinjiang are Ploughed to Use Clean Energy
More than 6,000 pentagonal helioscopes, each 48 square meters, are arranged neatly in a circle, such as a silver "sunflower field," which rotates with the sun and reflects the sun's rays to a heat-absorbing tower more than 200 meters high in the center to realize power generation.
The reporter saw this scene on the 25th in the Hami molten salt tower type photothermal power field of the CLP project in Maomaohu Town, Yigu County, Hami City, Xinjiang.
"The so-called molten salt tower type photothermal power generation means that the sun's rays are reflected through the mirror to the heat absorbing tower to form heat energy, and then the heat energy is converted into electricity through traditional power generation technology."
Zhang Yong, deputy general manager of CLP Hami Solar Thermal Power Co., Ltd., said that the design principle is similar to that of solar stoves used in rural areas in Northwest China, all of which need to gather the sunlight.
Construction of the power plant began in October 2017 and was connected to the grid by the end of last year. It covers an area of 6,600 acres and plans to install a total of 14,500 fixed helioscopes.
"Compared to traditional solar power generation technology, its biggest advantage is that it can store the accumulated heat energy and also generate electricity at night."
Zhang Yong said that the 13-hour heat storage system configured by the project will enable the generator set to maintain continuous and stable operation, which will not be affected by changes in light. It can also quickly participate in the peak adjustment of the power grid according to the demand of the peak load of the power grid.
When fully completed, the project will generate 198 million degrees of electricity annually, save more than 60,000 tons of standard coal per year, reduce sulfur dioxide emissions by more than 60 tons, nitrogen oxides by more than 60 tons, soot by about 20 tons and carbon dioxide by more than 150,000 tons, providing a steady stream of clean energy for the local area.
In addition, there is another silver "sunflower field" in the Shichengzi Photovoltaic Industrial Park in Hami City.
The Hamifu solar photovoltaic power plant covers an area of more than 2,300 acres, and the 714 power generation devices that have been built also follow the sun's rotation, keeping the sun's rays at a right angle of 90 degrees to the condenser surface.
"We use dual-axis tracking condenser power generation technology. Through unified integrated control, all power generation equipment will adjust the angle according to the height of the sun to maintain the efficiency of power generation."
Duan Mengqi, the station manager of the power station, said that under good weather conditions, the efficiency of the power generation technology can be increased by about 20% compared to the traditional photovoltaic power generation.
In the first half of this year, the power station has generated more than 7 million degrees of electricity, complementing the local demand for electricity.
Shichengzi Photovoltaic Industrial Park is a photovoltaic industrial demonstration park with the largest monomer scale and the most complete photovoltaic module type in Xinjiang, with a total of 38 photovoltaic power generation projects, with a total installed capacity of 820,000 kilowatts.
In the first half of this year, the electricity generation exceeded 110 million degrees, an increase of 6% compared to the same period in 2019.
Hami is one of the regions with the best solar energy resources in China.
The average annual total solar radiation is more than 6,200 megajoules per square meter, and the annual sunshine hours are about 3,200 hours.
In recent years, the city has vigorously developed the photovoltaic industry and planted "sunflower fields."
More than 2.5 million kilowatts of solar power has been installed. In the first half of this year, the city generated more than 1.4 billion degrees of photovoltaic power, a year-on-year increase of about 14 percent.
At present, there are more than 330 grid-connected photovoltaic power plants in Xinjiang with an installed capacity of more than 10 million kilowatts.
This year's annual photovoltaic power generation is expected to reach 15 billion degrees, which can replace more than 6 million tons of standard coal.
