France ramps up military spending in space - Xinhua
French Defense Minister Florence Parly said on the 24th that France will increase its space defense budget by hundreds of millions of euros and develop military forces in space to guard against "unfriendly actions" that other countries may make in outer space.
Parly told La Provence the same day that between 2019 and 2025, the budget for France's military space program will increase to 4.3 billion euros ($5 billion), up from 3.6 billion euros ($4.2 billion) previously proposed.
According to the French Military Planning Act 2019-2025, approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to update its existing observation and communications satellites, launch three electromagnetic listening satellites, and modernize its space surveillance radar.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced in July last year that the French Air Force would establish a Space Military Command and an "Aerospace and Space Force."
Parly said she will formally announce the creation of the Space Force when she visits a military academy in Salon, Provence, later.
The Space Force, which is part of the Air Force, will have 500 personnel by 2025, Parly said.
"The idea that space serves the common interests of science is gone forever," she said. "Today, space is a place where nations compete for global supremacy."
Parly reiterated Macron's previous remarks, saying the French side has no intention of provoking an arms race.
"We are by no means engaged in an arms race, but it is my duty to fully recognize the threats we may face."
Parly recounted the 2017 surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy.
"Peeping" is a Russian satellite, she said.
The Russian side denies this claim.
Parly said France will "very soon" have small patrol satellites capable of detecting and targeting "those behind unfriendly moves."
According to French media, France is seeking to establish a space force because US President Donald Trump asked the US Department of Defense last February to draft a bill for the creation of a space force.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act into law last December, authorizing the creation of the Pacific Air Force, the sixth largest military service in the US.
Some experts worry that these moves by the US have accelerated the pace of militarization of US space and may trigger a new round of space arms race.
