The overall stability of employment and prices shows that the economy has a "temperature"
Lin Huochan, reporter of Economic Daily and China Economic Network
In the first half of this year, in the face of the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic, China made overall efforts to promote epidemic prevention and control and economic and social development. The situation of epidemic prevention and control continued to improve, and the steady recovery of the economy was evident. Employment and price performance, which are closely related to people's livelihood, were generally stable. The Chinese economy handed over a report card of economic operation with a temperature.
In the first two months of this year, the surveyed unemployment rate rose.
Especially in February, the production and operation activities of many enterprises were basically shut down, the employment demand of enterprises decreased, the recruitment was delayed or canceled, and the surveyed unemployment rate in urban areas increased.
With the gradual improvement of the situation of epidemic prevention and control, the order of production and life of the whole society has been continuously restored.
The CPC Central Committee adheres to the general tone of seeking progress while maintaining stability, further intensifies macro policy hedging, comprehensively strengthens the employment priority policy, and actively promotes the work of aiding enterprises to stabilize and expand employment.
China has increased policy hedging to stabilize jobs, launched a policy combination of "relief and reprieve," reduced and exempted the contributions of three social insurance units in a phased manner, allowed deferred payment of social insurance premiums, expanded the benefits of unemployment insurance for small and medium-sized enterprises and work-for-hire training policies, and provided subsidies and traineeships for enterprises to absorb employment of key groups.
With the implementation of various policies to stabilize employment, the employment demand of enterprises has steadily picked up, the employment situation has gradually improved, and the surveyed unemployment rate in urban areas has gradually declined. In June, the surveyed unemployment rate was 5.7 percent.
Zhang Yi, director of the Department of Population and Employment Statistics of the National Bureau of Statistics, said that in the second quarter, various employment policies continued to bear fruit, and the labor force that exited earlier due to the impact of the epidemic returned one after another. In June, the labor force participation rate in urban areas increased by about 10 percentage points compared to February, which is close to the level of the same period last year.
According to the data, total urban employment increased by more than 19 percent in June compared to February, with most industries reaching pre-epidemic levels. The average working hours of employees in enterprises reached 46.8 hours per week, 6.6 hours higher than in February and 0.1 hours higher than in January.
Prices are also linked to thousands of households.
In January, the year-on-year rise in the CPI was 5.4%, the highest in years.
In February, the year-on-year rate of CPI growth declined slightly, but it was still in the "5 range."
The year-on-year rise in the CPI is at a high level, driven by both consumer demand before the Spring Festival, as well as the wrong month for the Spring Festival and a low year-on-year base.
However, the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on prices has been particularly pronounced.
Affected by the epidemic prevention and control, in January and February, all over the country, there were delays in logistics, untimely supplies of materials, and increased transportation costs of materials. In addition, some citizens hoarded and snapped up goods, and the prices of some necessities of life increased significantly.
In order to cope with the disruption caused by the epidemic prevention and control to the price situation, relevant departments have included important daily necessities in the scope of emergency transportation guarantee to ensure the smooth transportation of materials.
Under the influence of a series of policies and measures, the supply of vegetables, fruits and melons in the market is effectively guaranteed.
In order to cope with the rapid rise in pork prices at the beginning of this year, after the central government promulgated the policy of maintaining supply and price stability, all regions and departments quickly implemented it. The supply of pork reserves improved markedly, the production capacity of pigs was restored in an orderly manner, and the production and marketing order gradually became normal.
Since March, the price of pork has been falling continuously. In May, the year-on-year increase in food prices fell to 10.6%. In June, the price of pork rose slightly on a month-on-month basis due to factors such as a slowdown in the production of pigs, a decrease in imports and a rebound in the demand for group consumption.
Seasonal changes in fresh vegetable prices were evident, with an average increase of 3.4% in the first half of the year.
Affected by the relatively high base in the same period last year, fresh fruit prices continued to decline year-on-year, falling by an average of 13.3% in the first half of the year.
The basic livelihood of the masses has been effectively guaranteed and the overall economic and social situation has remained stable and orderly.
With the gradual resumption of transportation and logistics, the supply and demand situation in the market has improved.
Since March, the CPI has declined for four consecutive months, and the year-on-year rate of increase has dropped from 4.3% in March to 2.5% in June. Overall, the price level has returned to a stable level.
In the second half of the year, China's prices will remain at a moderate level, with little overall inflationary pressure. However, it is still necessary to promote the restoration of production and living order under the premise of doing a good job in normalizing epidemic prevention and control.
We will effectively deal with natural disasters such as floods and droughts in major agricultural producing areas such as grain, fruits and vegetables, strengthen market supervision, and resolutely crack down on acts such as hoarding and price gouging that disrupt market order.
