Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to sue the school after his college playground was smashed up?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed and the children were compensated and then sued the school.
Zhao Yifan, Correspondent of this newspaper
3-year-old Xiao Wen was playing in a college playground when he was accidentally hit on the head by Chen Mou of the softball team while pitching.
After Chen's compensation, Xiao Wen's father, Mr. Wen, as Xiao Wen's legal representative, took the school to court to demand an apology from the school where the playground was located, and to pay a total of 20,000 yuan in medical expenses and compensation for mental damage.
Recently, the People's Court of Haidian District of Beijing held after hearing the case that the school had set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, and had done its due duty of safety and security, and Chen had already made compensation. Accordingly, the judgment dismissed the plaintiff's lawsuit.
Mr. Wen alleges that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiao Wen to play on the school playground while the softball team was training on the playground.
In order to avoid the risk, Xiao Wen, Mr. Wen and many other children and their parents are in the safe area designated by the softball team.
But then Chen, a member of the softball team, took off his hands while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the protective net into the aforementioned safe area and hit Xiao Wen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiao Wen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believes that the facilities of the school's stadium do not comply with the relevant safety regulations and do not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The negligence of the school led to the above-mentioned incident, which caused Xiao Wen to suffer great physical and mental pain, and also brought great pain to his family members. The school should bear legal responsibility for this.
In this regard, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net in the playground, and posted management regulations and training notices, informing them that they should keep a safe distance from the training ground and reminding them to pay attention to their own safety. The plaintiff also could not prove that the school "failed to fulfill its safety and security obligations," and therefore did not agree to the compensation.
After hearing the case, the court held that the site involved in the incident is a venue open to the public free of charge. Although the school has safety and security obligations for the management of the playground, such safety and security obligations only need to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the accident, the school had set up a protective net in the playground, and had fulfilled the proper safety and security obligations. Moreover, Chen also compensated Xiao Wen for medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses of more than 2,000 yuan in accordance with the compensation agreement previously reached. The two sides agreed to settle the dispute at one time.
Afterwards, Xiao Wen's parents once again claimed compensation from the school, which was unfounded. The court ruled to dismiss all the plaintiffs' claims.
After the verdict was handed down, neither side appealed, and the verdict is now in effect.
According to the provisions of Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, schools, as managers of public places, have the obligation to guarantee safety; in the case of damage caused by the actions of a third party, the third party shall bear the liability for tort, while the managers of public places who fail to fulfill the obligation of safeguarding safety shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
The judge said that as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the whole place, foresee the possible danger and damage, and thus is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the loss or mitigate the extent of the damage, and the cost of avoiding and mitigating the damage is the lowest. Therefore, the law stipulates that he shall bear the corresponding security obligations for engaging in social activities.
In this case, for unspecified groups of people entering the playground, which is open to the public free of charge, the safety and security obligations of the school should be commensurate with the social activities it engages in. In particular, the school should take basic safety measures and have the obligation to inform about hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is also not appropriate to impose too high security obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has already set up a protective net and has done its duty to inform, it can be determined that the school is not at fault and should not be held liable.
In addition, for third party infringement, even if the administrators of schools and other public places fail to fulfill their safety and security obligations, their liability is a kind of compensation for damages. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, after the administrators assume the supplementary liability, they can also recover from the third party.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victims should not expand the scope of claims after they have received compensation from the direct infringer.
