Yang Hongnian, Founder of Beijing Philharmonic Choir, Dies at 86 - Xinhua
Beijing News (Reporter Liu Zhen) On July 26, the Beijing Philharmonic Choir published an obituary. Yang Hongnian, the founder of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir, a famous Chinese conductor, music educator, lifelong academic member of the Central Conservatory of Music and professor of the Department of Conducting, died at 13:55 on July 26,2020 in Beijing. He was 86 years old.
Photo courtesy of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir website.
Born in 1934, Yang Hongnian is a native of Nanjing, Jiangsu Province, and loved music from an early age.
In 1951, he was the conductor of the choir of Nanjing People's Radio Station. In the fall of 1951, he was admitted to the music department of East China Normal University in Shanghai, where he studied conducting under Professor Yang Jiaren and German conductor Hizmann. Alzamanov, a former Soviet expert, studied music style and polyphony.
In 1958, he taught at the Department of Music of Beijing Normal College of Arts, and in 1973, he was transferred to the Department of Composition and Conducting of Central Conservatory of Music.
Yang Hongnian founded the Beijing Philharmonic Choir in 1983.
Over the past 30 years, adhering to the tenet of "love and dedication," he has led this choir to sing all over the world, and won dozens of awards in important competitions at home and abroad.
He has conducted the performances of more than 30 groups, including the Central Orchestra Choir, the Central Ethnic Song and Dance Troupe, the Oriental Song and Dance Troupe, and the Shanghai Choir, and held many symphony concerts and choral concerts.
His works include "Orchestral Training," "Choral Training," "Two Song Writing," "Children's Song Collection" (top and bottom volumes) and his thesis "On the Problem of Choral Intonation," "On the Layout of Orchestral Music Sound Levels," as well as his translations of "Choral Instruments" and "Debussy's Harmonic Language."
