Israel Strengthens Repeated Prevention and Control of Epidemic Diseases - CNN.com
2020-07-26 04:56:44 Source: Guangming Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sishuo
Israel steps up prevention and control of repeated outbreaks
In the early days of the outbreak of COVID-19, Israel's prevention and control measures have shown remarkable results.
However, with the gradual lifting of the lockdown, the number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Israel has increased significantly recently, and the Israeli government has taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic on several occasions.
On February 28, the first case of COVID-19 was confirmed in Israel, which quickly closed all ports of entry and exit, suspended non-essential businesses, switched schools to online classes, restricted public transportation and non-essential social activities, locked down cities with severe epidemics, and jointly maintained prevention and control measures by the military and police.
This series of measures quickly yielded positive results, and by mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 in a single day in Israel had dropped back to single digits.
As the epidemic was brought under control and Israel's various prevention and control measures were fully unsealed, the number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 has gradually rebounded since June.
Especially after entering July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, the number of daily new cases in Israel has been above 1,500 for eight days, and as of the time of publication on July 25, the number of daily new cases reached 916.
As of July 25, Israel had 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths.
In the face of the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases topped 30,000, the Israeli government closed gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other public entertainment venues, and introduced a policy of restricting public transportation, limiting the number of passengers per bus to a maximum of 20.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of "sealing off the city" on weekends, stipulating that "sealing off the city" will be implemented from 17:00 on Fridays to 5:00 on Sundays.
During this period, people will be allowed to go out, but shops, shopping centers, hairdressers, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while essential services such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people will be banned on all dates and times, gyms, studios and other venues will be closed, restaurants and cafes will be banned from serving food, and only take-away services will be allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people did not pay enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and failed to join forces with the government in the fight against the epidemic.
After the recurrence of the epidemic in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest against the government's prevention and control measures affecting their own economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people demonstrated in Tel Aviv, arguing that anti-pandemic policies were affecting the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's official residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's decision to ban restaurants, cafes and other prevention and control measures without giving compensation.
In addition, many people do not observe the rules of wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters when they are outdoors. To avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chins or on their wrists.
During repeated epidemics, the school was the hardest-hit area for the spread of the new coronavirus. According to the reporter's recent visit to the kindergarten, the teachers and students of the kindergarten did not wear masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, thus laying a hidden danger for a large number of teachers and students to be infected with the virus.
Professor Eli Waxman, a member of the Israeli National Security Council's expert advisory group on combating the epidemic, said Israel is heading toward a "dangerous situation," pointing out that the current epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel are not enough, and that all leisure and entertainment venues and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks a master plan to fight the epidemic, and the parliament and various government departments should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on combating the epidemic, and formulate clear steps including relevant restrictions for different departments.
