On the afternoon of the 25th local time, a small plane crashed into the top floor of a multi-storey residential building in Wessel County, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany, killing three people in total.
Duisburg prosecutors, the Wessel County Police Department and the Wessel City Fire Department issued a joint statement late in the day, saying that at about 14:40 that day, a pair of small planes crashed into the penthouse of a multi-story residential building on Wessel County's Whipperscamp Street, killing three.
It took off from the city of Marr in the Ruhr district of North Rhine-Westphalia on the same day, stopped at the airport in Wessel County and took off again before crashing into a residential building.
The deceased may have been identified as a female occupant of the home that was hit and two passengers on the small plane.
A two-year-old child in the room suffered only minor injuries and was safely rescued.
The rest of the occupants of the room were not injured in the accident, but the mood has not been calmed.
Footage from the scene, reported by the German news agency DPA, showed smoke billowing from the house where the accident occurred. After firefighters extinguished the fire, they could see that the house was badly damaged.
At present, the cause of the plane crash is not clear.
The Rheinische Post, citing the police, reported that there were clues that the plane had broken up before it hit the residential building.
The police said that several parts of the plane were found in the area of the accident site.
The German Interpol is working with the Duisburg prosecutor's office and the German Federal Aviation Accident Investigation Bureau to investigate the cause of the accident.
The reporter learned from the Chinese Consulate General in Dusseldorf on the same day that the museum contacted the local police department and the fire department. According to the judgement of the scene, there were no Chinese citizens among the casualties.
