The largest earthquake to hit Taiwan this year occurred in the eastern waters of Taiwan - CNN.com
Taipei, July 26/PRNewswire/-- At 20:52 on July 26, an earthquake measuring 6.1 on the Richter scale occurred in the eastern waters of Taiwan, with a maximum magnitude of 4. The earthquake was felt across Taiwan, making it the largest earthquake in Taiwan this year.
The Taiwan Meteorological Department reported that the epicenter of the earthquake was located 86.5 kilometers southeast of Yilan County Government, or the eastern waters of Taiwan, at a depth of 53 kilometers, according to the Central News Agency, Zhongshi Electronic News and ETtoday News Cloud.
The China Earthquake Network put the magnitude at 5.5.
The largest tremors in Taiwan were 4 in Hualien County, 3 in Yilan County, Taitung County, Nantou County and Yunlin County, and 1 to 2 in other counties and cities.
The Taiwan Meteorological Department pointed out that this earthquake is the largest in Taiwan since the beginning of this year, and it is a subduction zone earthquake at the junction of plates. The epicenter of this earthquake has often occurred in the past, and it has been relatively active since this year.
In the coming week, it is still not ruled out that there will still be aftershocks of magnitude 4 or above.
